<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="comparisons">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Comparisons and diagnostic notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bernhauer" authorityYear="1938" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Megarthrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megarthrus dentipes" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dentipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Megarthrus dentipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. flavolimbatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="flavolimbatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">M. flavolimbatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. hemipterus" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="hemipterus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">M. hemipterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. panda" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="panda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">M. panda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. are the only members of the genus to have the anterior frontal margin carinate, the antennae bearing short and dense pubescence only on antennomeres 5-11, hemispherical eyes with the highest point above level of the vertex, the lateral sides of pronotum and elytra slightly deplanate, the prohypomera without a marked ridge, and the pubescence on abdominal tergites parallel. Within these species 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. panda" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="panda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">M. panda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. can be easily distinguished by the shape posterior legs of the males (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 24–32" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 24 - 32. Megarthrus panda sp. nov., aedeagus in ventral 24 and lateral 25 views; metatibiae 26 mesotibiae 27 mesotrochanter and mesofemur 28 metatrochanter and metafemur 29 tergite VIII in lateral 30 and ventral 31 views sternite VIII in ventral view 32. Scale bar: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1056.66553.figures24-32" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/578549" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">26</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 24–32" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 24 - 32. Megarthrus panda sp. nov., aedeagus in ventral 24 and lateral 25 views; metatibiae 26 mesotibiae 27 mesotrochanter and mesofemur 28 metatrochanter and metafemur 29 tergite VIII in lateral 30 and ventral 31 views sternite VIII in ventral view 32. Scale bar: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1056.66553.figures24-32" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/578549" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">29</figureCitation>
). Its genitalia are also diagnostic, notably in the male by the aedeagal ventral wall strongly sinuate in lateral view (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 24–32" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figures 24 - 32. Megarthrus panda sp. nov., aedeagus in ventral 24 and lateral 25 views; metatibiae 26 mesotibiae 27 mesotrochanter and mesofemur 28 metatrochanter and metafemur 29 tergite VIII in lateral 30 and ventral 31 views sternite VIII in ventral view 32. Scale bar: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1056.66553.figures24-32" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/578549" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">25</figureCitation>
), and in the female by the arcuate dorsal genital sclerite slightly wider at middle in combination with the dorsobasal margin of the gonocoxal plate evenly narrowed to its truncate median portion projecting anterad (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 33–40" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figures 33 - 40. Megarthrus panda sp. nov., female genital segments, dorsal part in ventral view 33 and ventral part in dorsal 34 and lateral 35 views antenna 36 female tergite VIII in lateral 37 and dorsal 38 views male left hemitergite IX 39 female sternite VIII in ventral view 40. Scale bar: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1056.66553.figures33-40" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/578550" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">34</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Distribution and natural history.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
The species is endemic to Yunnan Province (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 41" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 41. Distribution map in China of Megarthrus dentipes Bernhauer, M. flavolimbatus Cameron, M. hemipterus (Illiger) and Megarthrus panda sp. nov. Scale bar: 300 km." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1056.66553.figure41" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/578551" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">41</figureCitation>
), where it was found at elevations ranging from 2290 to 2700 m a. s. l. from July to September by sifting leaf litter with mushrooms in mixed deciduous forests with alder, oak and pine.
</paragraph>
